09301nam a22011055i 9782759803170DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212008fr     fo  d z      eng d  a97827598031707 a10.1051/978-2-7598-0317-02doi  a(DE-B1597)574850  a(OCoLC)1248760152  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  afrcFR 7aSCI0130002bisacsh1 aSpotheim-Maurizot, Mélanie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRadiation Chemistry :bFrom basics to applications in material and life sciences /cThierry Douki, Mehran Mostafavi, Jacqueline Belloni, Mélanie Spotheim-Maurizot. 1aLes Ulis : bEDP Sciences, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (322 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tList of authors -- tPart I / Primary radiation-induced phenomena -- tChapter 1 An overview of the radiation chemistry of liquids -- tChapter 2 Tools for radiolysis studies -- tChapter 3 The solvated electron: a singular chemical species -- tChapter 4 Water radiolysis under extreme conditions. Application to the nuclear industry -- tPart II / Radiation chemistry mechanisms and applications -- tChapter 5 Molecular formation in the interstellar medium -- tChapter 6 Water remediation by the electron beam treatment -- tChapter 7 Metal clusters and nanomaterials -- tChapter 8 Water radiolysis in cement-based materials -- tChapter 9 Obtaining high performance polymeric materials by irradiation -- tChapter 10 Radiosterilization of drugs -- tChapter 11 Food irradiation: wholesomeness and treatment control -- tIII / Radiation damage to biomolecules, radioprotection and radiotherapy -- tChapter 12 Radiation-induced damage to DNA: from model compounds to cell -- tChapter 13 Mechanisms of direct radiation damage to DNA -- tChapter 14 Charge motion in DNA -- tChapter 15 Genome maintenance mechanisms in response to radiation-induced DNA damage -- tChapter 16 Pulse radiolysis studies of free radical processes in peptides and proteins -- tChapter 17 Radiation-induced damage of membrane lipids and lipoproteins -- tChapter 18 Predicting radiation damage distribution in biomolecules -- tChapter 19 Chemical protection against ionizing radiation -- tChapter 20 Advances in radiotherapy : new principles -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book gives a progress report on the many and original contributions of radiation chemistry to the fundamental knowledge of the vast domain of chemical reactions and its applications. Radiation chemistry techniques indeed make it possible to elucidate detailed physicochemical mechanisms in inorganic and organic chemistry (including in space) and in biochemistry. Moreover, this comprehension is applied in materials science to precisely control syntheses by radiation, such as radiopolymerisation, radiografting, specific treatment of surfaces (textiles, paintings, inks, etc.), synthesis of complex nanomaterials, degradation of environmental pollutants and radioresistance of materials for nuclear reactors. In life sciences, the study of the effects of radiation on biomacromolecules (DNA, proteins, lipids) not only permits the comprehension of normal or pathological biological mechanisms, but also the improvement of our health. In particular, many advances in cancer radiotherapy, in the radioprotection of nuclear workers and the general population, as well as in the treatment of diseases and the radiosterilization of drugs, could be obtained thanks to this research. Abundantly illustrated and written in English by top international specialists who have taken care to render the subjects accessible, this work will greatly interest those curious about a scientific field that is new to them and students attracted by the original and multidisciplinary aspects of the field. At a time when radiation chemistry research is experiencing spectacular development in numerous countries, this book will attract many newcomers to the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aChemistry. 4aNuclear. 7aSCIENCE / Chemistry / General.2bisacsh1 aAlbert, Monique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmourette, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldacchino, Gérard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalosso, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelloni, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlin, Yuri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernhard, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBobrowski, Krzysztof, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouniol, Pascal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuxton, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCadet, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastaing, Bertrand, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoqueret, Xavier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidkova, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawes, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouki, Thierry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDouki, Thierry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmi, Salvatore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForay, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHickel, Bernard, econtri